{"key":"post-15945324","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>15945324</id>\n<content>Doing a white balance on perlite in a terrarium in bright daylight is essentially how I came up with the figure of 5000K to 7000K as being optimum for mushroom growing, after noticing that mushrooms grew much better when a terrarium was set outdoors in sunlight for several minutes per day.&amp;nbsp; You can use your naked eye though.&amp;nbsp; The perlite should be white, but with an almost imperceptible blue tint.&amp;nbsp; Of course, these days our lamps are labeled in color temperature so it's much easier on us.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Of course, if you're growing outdoors it's like taking a fat girl to the prom.&amp;nbsp; You dance with what you brought.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>15945655</next>\n<prev>15945312</prev>\n<first>15945231</first>\n<last>15945706</last>\n<when>1331733180</when>\n<utime>03/14/12 04:53 PM</utime>\n</post>"}